admissions applied to Free Schools and New Academies will prevent the Church from meeting a growing need for places in metropolitan areas</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and place further pressur</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">e on existing Catholic provision</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Catholic Education Service </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">requests the opportunity to open a Catholic </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Free </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">School without the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> faith based</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> admissions cap to meet a demand for Catholic </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">places within a Local Authority. We believe that a Catholic Free S</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">chool should be able to have the same admissions rules as all existing Catholic schools.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">An overview of Catholic education</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The Catholic Education Service</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> (CES)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> acts on behalf of the Catholic Bishops’ Conference, representing the 22 dioceses of England and</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Wales to promote and sustain Catholic education. We have a strong and</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> positive working relationship with the Department for Education, sharing the aims of high academic standards for all and increased parental choice.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Catholic schools make up 10% of the n</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ational total of maintained schools. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">There are currently 2163 Catholic schools</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, academies</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and colleges in England </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">educating 812,212 pupils</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">There are 23</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">0</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Catholic academies with over a quarter of all Catholic secondary schools converted to academy status.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Catholic schools serve more diverse and disadvantaged communities reflecting the multicultural nature of the Catholic community, many of whom come from the new and old migrant communities. 34.5% of pupils in Catholic maintained primary schools are from eth</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">nic minority backgrounds compared with 28.5% nationally. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> 30.2% of pupils in Catholic maintained secondary schools are from ethnic minority backgrounds compared with 24.2% nationally. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">18.4% </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">of pupils at Catholic maintained </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">primary</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> schools live in the most deprived areas compared with</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> 13.8% nationally. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">17.3% of pupils at Catholic maintained secondary schools live in the most deprived areas compared with 12.2</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">%</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> nationally</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> (Source: Department for Education School Census &amp; CES Census)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Despite these challenges Catholic schools maintain high educational standards at all levels. 82% of Catholic primary schools have Ofsted grades of good or outstanding compared to 79% nationally. At GCSE, Catholic schools outperform the national average by</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> 5% and at age 11, Catholic schools outperform the national average English and Maths SATs scores by 5%.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">The importance of control over admission</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">s f</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">or Catholic schools</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Retaining full control over admissions criteria, alongside governance, own</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ership</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and em</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ployment of staff is central to the continuing success of Catholic education. The Catholic Bishops have a duty laid down in Canon Law (</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">c.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">796) to ensure there is an adequate supply of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">C</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">atholic schools for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">C</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">atholic parents seeking a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">C</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">atholic education for th</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">eir child. The control over admissions enable the Bishops to fulfil</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">this duty.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">As Catholic schools are academically successful and often very popular with families the Church must ensure that its limited resources, namely the Church owned land and building</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s, financial contribution </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">from the local Catholic community and a supply of successful Catholic leaders, are effectively utilised in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">an accountable and transparent manner for the benefit of the Catholic community.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Catholic schools have always had control o</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ver their own admission</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">successive </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">government</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> going back to the 19</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:super">th</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Century </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">have supported</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> governing bodies </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">controlling</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">their own</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> admissions, this can be seen in the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">1944 Education Act</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and subsequent Education Acts, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and the 2010 Academies Act</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Free Schools and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">n</span><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">ew Academies cap on faith based admissions</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Unlike converter academies, where Catholic schools transfer their existing admissions arrangements, Free Schools and new Academies have an arbitrary cap placed upon faith based admissions. This c</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ap stems from the coalition agreement and is not set out in legislation. </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We believe that parental choice is essential in the diverse education system and continue to work with the government to ensure that parental choice is not undermined. We are keen to</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> participate in the Government’s Free School Programme and recognise that this can be one way of supporting parental choice whilst meaning a demand for school places within the Catholic sector.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The Catholic community is diverse and inclusive and the pupil </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">population in Catholic schools reflects this. The introduction of a cap on admission </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">prevents the Catholic sector from engaging with this flagship government programme</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and so inhibits the Catholic Church’s mission to provide</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> a high standard of education fo</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">r children from a range of socio-economic backgrounds</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The channelling of government funding towards these new types of school places greater pressures on the Catholic sector </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">in the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> struggle to meet the needs of the Catholic community</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, particularly in mor</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">e deprived inner city areas,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> to provide a high standard education within the Catholic faith.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">A review of the admission cap on </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Free </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">S</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">chool</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">s &amp; new A</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">cademies</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">As the largest provider of secondary education and a supporter of successive governments’ policy in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">promoting parental choice within the education system, the Catholic Education Service</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> in partnership with the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">relevant</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Diocesan</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">E</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ducation </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">C</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ommissions</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">requests the opportunity to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">open</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> a Catholic Free school without a cap on faith based admissions.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">This sc</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">hools would meet the local need for Catholic spaces in a metropolitan area where there is a growing demands for Catholic places.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We hope the Education Committee will acknowledge the unique contribution that Catholic schools </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">make</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and recommend this pilot sc</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">heme to the Minster.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">December 2013</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>